Victory in the Pacific.

Today in 1945, Japanese Emperor Hirohito announced the Japanese government’s surrender in a radio address to the empire. World War II in the Pacific had come to an end.

📷: "American servicemen and women gather in front of "Rainbow Corner" Red Cross club in Paris to celebrate the unconditional surrender of the Japanese." National Archives, Records of the Office of the Chief Signal Officer. (111-SC-210241)

node.text:
A once every 42 years type of 📸

Using the onboard Wide Field Planetary Camera 2, the Hubble Space Telescope captured this rare edge-on view of the ring system of the planet Uranus, on this day in 2007. Astronomers on Earth can only see the rings' edge every 42 years due to the planet's 84 year orbit. In fact, the last time the rings were tilted edge-on to Earth, astronomers didn't even know they existed.

node.text:
A heroes’ welcome.

On August 13, 1969, the Apollo 11 astronauts were given a heroes' welcome in New York City with a ticker-tape parade through the Canyon of Heroes. It was reported that a record tonnage of paper was dropped by enthusiastic citizens during the parade.

On the same day, the astronauts received the Presidential Medal of Freedom, the nation's highest civilian honor.

Fly free, Enterprise.
On this day in 1977, Space Shuttle Enterprise, crewed by astronauts Fred Haise and Gordon Fullerton, made its first free flight from a 747 during Shuttle Approach & Landing Tests. This NASA photo was taken soon after Enterprise and the 747 Shuttle Carrier Aircraft separated for the free flight and Enterprise's glide landing.

node.text:
To space and back again.
This Discoverer XIII reentry capsule was the first human-made object to be recovered from orbit. "Discoverer" was the cover name for the highly classified Air Force/CIA Corona photoreconnaissance satellite program.
It was recovered north of Hawaii by the U.S. Navy on this day in 1960, one day after it was launched from Vandenberg Air Force Base. While the Discoverer XIII satellite did not carry cameras or film, and the capsule contained only diagnostic instruments, other Corona satellites carried cameras and film beginning with Discoverer XIV one week later. By the end of the Corona program in May 1972, over 120 Corona satellites had successfully flown and photographed the Soviet Union, China, and other nations. #AirSpacePhoto

Even before we had a building of our own, Air and Space artifacts had a home on the National Mall in Washington, DC.

Aircraft like the 1903 Wright Flyer, Lockheed Vega Winnie Mae, and the Spirit of St. Louis were on display at the Smithsonian’s Arts & Industries Building before finding their permanent homes at our flagship building on the National Mall. #Smithsonian175

node.text:
Did you know that in 1936, Aeronautics was an Olympic event? 🥇✈️
Switzerland’s Hermann Schreiber was awarded an Olympic gold medal for merit in Aeronautics for a glider flight that took place over the Alps in 1935! And there were plenty of actual aeronautical feats to witness at the Berlin games. The Hindenburg hovered in the skies over the Olympic stadium, painted with the Olympic rings. The first public demonstration of the Messerschmitt Bf 109 prototype took place. And the Museum's Bücker Bü-133C Jungmeister was there too! 
Captain Alexander Papana of the Rumanian Air Force had placed fourth in the two-man bobsled event in the 1932 Lake Placid Olympics and had won the gold medal in the 1933 World Championships. Papana participated in the Olympics aeronautics demonstrations in 1936 and his Bücker Bü-133C Jungmeister, pictured here, featured Olympic rings on its tail. #Olympics

node.text:
Splashdown! 50 years ago today, Apollo 15 returned to Earth as command module Endeavour splashed down in the Pacific Ocean. One of the three Apollo 15 parachutes failed to inflate fully, so descent velocity was 2.8 mph faster than planned. The capsule was designed to land safely with just two parachutes, so the crew was OK.
After splashdown, the astronauts were assisted out of the command module by Navy divers and were flown to the recovery ship USS Okinawa by helicopter. The Apollo 15 astronauts were the first lunar surface explorers to not be quarantined after their mission. #Apollo50

node.text:
On this day in 1945, the Boeing B-29 Superfortress "Enola Gay" dropped atomic bomb “Little Boy” on Hiroshima, Japan. It was the first time an atomic weapon was used in combat.

The Boeing B-29 Superfortress was the most advanced propeller-driven airplane in the world in 1945, making it the ultimate definition of a “modern” airplane. Designed to fly farther, faster, and higher than any other bomber, the combination of the B-29’s aerodynamic, structural and propulsion innovations allowed it to carry 5,000 pounds of bombs to a target 1,500 miles away while cruising at 220 miles per hour at altitudes up to 30,000 feet. It also had advanced tricycle landing gear and was the first bomber to have an analog computer-controlled defensive armament system and a pressurized and heated fuselage that meant the 11-person crew did not have to wear oxygen masks and heavy, bulky clothing during long missions.

"Enola Gay" is currently on display at the Steven F. Udvar-Hazy Center in Chantilly, Virginia.

node.text:
Today in 1943, the Women Airforce Service Pilots (WASP) was officially formed.

With the merging of the Women Auxiliary Ferrying Squadron (WAFS) and the Women’s Flying Training Detachment (WFTD), the WASP flew 60 million miles during World War II, piloting military aircraft on domestic missions. These women flew the entire range of aircraft manufactured for the war.
#BecauseOfHerStory

node.text:
Rescuing people at sea has always been a hazardous undertaking — but for 231 years, the U.S. Coast Guard has risen to the challenge.
The Sikorsky HH-52A, the first @USCG aircraft to join our collection, helps us tell that story. The HH-52 was the Coast Guard’s first turbine-powered helicopter and the first that could land in the water next to vessels or personnel in distress without using awkward floats, making it the most effective air-sea rescue helicopter of its time. The Coast Guard operated 99 HH-52s between 1962 and 1989, saving 15,000 lives.
The Coast Guard was founded on this day in 1790.
